The term '''cotton ceiling''' refers to the difficulty [[transgender|trans people]] experience when seeking [[lesbian]] and [[gay]] relationships, and in lesbian and gay [[social space]]s more generally. A play on the similar term "[[glass ceiling]]"<ref name="paris">{{cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/sv/article/wd75n4/paris-lees-my-transgender-tinder-adventure-929|title=My Adventures Using Tinder as a Trans Woman|date=28 May 2015|website=Vice.com|accessdate=22 January 2018}}</ref>, the term was coined by [[Canadian]] trans woman and activist Drew DeVeaux.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://freethoughtblogs.com/nataliereed/2012/04/04/caught-up-in-cotton/|title=Caught Up In Cotton |last=Reed|first=Natalie|date=4 April 2012|website=Sincerely, Natalie Reed |publisher=FreeThoughtBlogs.com |access-date=9 December 2017 |quote= The term “Cotton Ceiling” was originally coined by the intensely awesome Canadian trans-activist and porn star Drew DeVeaux,}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=SnKQDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA103&lpg=PA103&dq=cotton+ceiling+trans&source=bl&ots=JpX6eCdVVj&sig=FbtUtPLw2frf6nmsnwtlgq9t4vc&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjavemavObYAhWHJ1AKHQgpCZk4FBDoATAGegQIBxAB#v=onepage&q=cotton+ceiling+trans&f=false|title=Feminist Perspectives on Orange Is the New Black: Thirteen Critical Essays|first1=April Kalogeropoulos|last1=Householder|first2=Adrienne|last2=Trier-Bieniek|date=30 June 2016|publisher=McFarland|accessdate=22 January 2018|via=Google Books}}</ref>
== Controversy ==
Some [[Transgender rights|trans rights activists]] have described this as [[transphobic]] [[social exclusion|exclusion]]. In 2014, [[Julia Serano]] wrote that "when the overwhelming majority of [[cisgender|cis]] [[Dyke (slang)|dykes]] date and fuck cis women, but are not open to, or are even turned off by, the idea of dating or fucking trans women, how is that not transphobic?"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/the-struggle-to-find-trans-love-in-san-francisco|title=The Struggle To Find Trans Love In San Francisco|website=thedailybeast.com|date=14 January 2014|accessdate=21 June 2014}}</ref> [[Cisgender]] lesbian Andrea Zanin wrote in 2013 that "a lot of cis and otherwise non-trans gals need to ... take the opportunity to really examine how much of our desire rests on [[cissexism]], and how much of the sexual culture we create and consume excludes trans women".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://transadvocate.com/if-trans-women-arent-welcome-neither-am-i_n_10232.htm|title=If trans women aren't welcome, neither am I|website=transadvocate.com|date=25 September 2013|accessdate=21 June 2014}}</ref>
However, other trans activists consider the concept problematic. Journalist [[Paris Lees]] wrote in 2015 that "there's a huge difference between denying someone a job versus not desiring someone sexually. Sexual attraction may be the one area that it's OK to 'discriminate' in—after all, it's up to you who you want to fuck—but you don't need to be a dick about your preference."<ref name="paris" /> Meanwhile, a 2013 [[Everyday Feminism]] article, written by an anonymous trans woman, stated that "the 'cotton ceiling' should be considered an unhelpful concept for this type of discussion and should be set aside by trans activists moving forward."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://everydayfeminism.com/2013/05/getting-with-girls-like-us/|title=Getting With Girls Like Us: A Radical Guide To Dating Trans Women For Cis Women|website=everydayfeminism.com|date=12 May 2013|accessdate=21 June 2018}}</ref>
The concept is almost universally condemned by [[Feminist views on transgender topics|anti-trans activists]]. Academic [[Sheila Jeffreys]] wrote in her 2014 book "Gender Hurts: A Feminist Analysis of the Politics of Transgenderism" that '[t]he campaign relies on guilt-tripping, in which women who resist are accused of transphobia or transmisogyny, in an attempt to induce them to admit unwanted penises to their bodies."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=kLhwAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA181&lpg=PA181&dq=cotton+ceiling+trans&source=bl&ots=4AwdJgbb6J&sig=QLAzz2Shhs-MFvujIEQmAcpWWHQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwijsZ_gvObYAhVRZlAKHQiFCIk4HhDoATAHegQIChAB#v=onepage&q=cotton+ceiling+trans&f=false|title=Gender Hurts: A Feminist Analysis of the Politics of Transgenderism|first=Sheila|last=Jeffreys|date=24 April 2014|publisher=Routledge|accessdate=22 January 2018|via=Google Books}}</ref>, while in the same year blogger Julian Vigo wrote on [[CounterPunch]] that "[w]hile many are sympathetic to the fact that trans women wish to be accepted within social circles as women, they find it preposterous that lesbians are now being asked to deny their sexuality as proof of their solidarity with trans women, least (sic) they be labelled a bigot."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.counterpunch.org/2013/06/07/the-left-hand-of-darkness/|title=The Left Hand of Darkness|website=counterpunch.org|date=7 June 2013|accessdate=21 June 2018}}</ref>
