[[File:Legal statuses of German in Europe.svg|thumb|right|450px|
Legal statuses of German in Europe:
{{legend|#ffcc00|'''"[[German Sprachraum]]"''': German is (co-)official language and first language of the majority of the population}}
{{legend|#d98575|German is a co-official language, but not the first language of the majority of the population}}
{{legend|#7373d9|German (or a German dialect) is a legally recognised minority language <small>(Squares: Geographic distribution too dispersed/small for map scale)</small>}}
{{legend|#30efe3|German (or a variety of German) is spoken by a sizeable minority, but has no legal recognition}}
]]
The '''{{lang|de|Rat für deutsche Rechtschreibung}}''' ({{IPA-de|ˈʁaːt fyːɐ̯ ˈdɔʏtʃə ˈʁɛçtˌʃʁaɪbʊŋ}}, "'''Council for German Orthography'''" or "'''Council for German Spelling'''"<ref name=goethe>{{cite web|url=https://www.goethe.de/en/spr/mag/20802137.html|title=German Spelling Reform - Nearly a Culture War|last=Dittrich|first=Monika|date=July 2016|publisher=[[Goethe-Institut]]|accessdate=4 February 2018}}</ref>), or '''{{lang|de|RdR}}''', is the main international body regulating [[German orthography]].

With its seat being in [[Mannheim]], [[Germany]], the RdR was formed in 2004 as a successor to the ''{{lang|de|Zwischenstaatliche Kommission für deutsche Rechtschreibung}}'' ("Intergovernmental Commission for German Orthography") in order to include supporters as well as opponents of the [[German orthography reform of 1996]] (and subsequent reforms).<ref name=goethe/><ref>[http://www.rechtschreibrat.com/DOX/statut.pdf Official statute of the Council for German Orthography]</ref>

Currently the RdR is composed of 41 members from those states and regions in the [[German Sprachraum]]:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rechtschreibrat.com/der-rat/ueber-den-rat/|title=Die Mitglieder|publisher=Council for German Orthography|language=de|accessdate=4 February 2018}}</ref>

* {{flag|Germany}}: 18 councillors
* {{flag|Austria}}: 9 councillors
* {{flag|Switzerland}}: 9 councillors
* {{flag|South Tyrol}} ([[Italy]]): 1 councillor
* {{BE-DE}} of [[Belgium]]: 1 councillor
* {{flag|Liechtenstein}}: 1 councillor
* {{flag|Luxembourg}}: 1 observer (no voting right)

Despite having German as one of its official languages, [[Luxembourg]], which was not involved in devising the reform of 1996, is not a full member of the council. The government of Luxembourg unilaterally adopted the reform.{{cn|date=February 2018}}

According to the duchy's largest newspaper, the ''{{lang|de|[[Luxemburger Wort]]}}'', Luxembourg does not perceive itself as a "German-speaking country" (the only national language is [[Luxembourgish]]) and thus had no right to take part in the council.<ref>''Luxemburger Wort'', 9 August 2004</ref> However, Luxembourg participates in {{lang|fr|[[La Francophonie]]}} and has members in the {{lang|fr|[[Académie française]]}}, despite [[French language|French]] being only a co-official language, just like German.<ref>{{lang|fr|[http://www.francophonie.org/Carte-interactive-des-Etats-et.html Carte interactive des Etats et gouvernements membres], Organisation internationale de la Francophonie}}</ref>

The chairman of the ''{{lang|de|[[Gesellschaft für deutsche Sprache]]}}'' ({{lang|de|GfdS}}) is a member of the council. In 2003, the RdR, the GfdS, the ''{{lang|de|[[Goethe-Institut]]}}'' and the Institute of the German Language, founded the German Language Council (''{{lang|de|Deutscher Sprachrat}}''), which was later also joined by the [[German Academic Exchange Service]] (DAAD).

